I have watched nearly every video of the Great Tohoku Earthquake I could find. It is a search for understanding and knowledge intermingled with sadness, regret and compassion for those lost in the devastation. On the practical side, I hope every town can build defenses that will protect people. On the other hand, I also know that there will be wild cards that drop the landmass 10 feet and nullify human defenses. It will always be a fight against time and nature. I sincerely hope our beautiful Japanese brethren are able to create a flexible, suitable and sustainable system of defenses against Nature and all her perils.

Japan was Instrumental in the recovery efforts for the 2004 Boxing day Tsunami, (the death tolle reaching upwards of 235,000 souls lost). They responded with millions in donations, and helicopters, and food, and teams of ground-searchers to help with the disaster. 7 years after this horrific event, they too would experience a disaster on a scale similar to the boxing day Tsunami. Thankfully, they were equipped with warning systems, and had previous experience with smaller quakes. Sadly, the sea walls provided a false sense of security. Many of the deaths were people inland, who didnt believe the Tsunami would breach the wall, and destroy their villages.  Japanese are strong, resilient people. Bless everyone who survived this terrifying disaster.

DEAR JAPAN, Hal yang perlu rakyat kalian tahu, dulu kalian menjajah negara kami (Indonesia), kalian mengeksploitasi SDA kami dan memaksa rakyat kami untuk melakukan kegiatan yang menguntungkan kalian, tanpa imbalan dan belas kasih terhadap rakyat kami, banyak rakyat kami yang menemui ajalnya karena tindakan Egois kalian, ini sangat merugikan bagi bangsa kami dan sangat menguntungkan bagi kalian untuk pertumbuhan ekonomi dan memberi kalian makan, itu sangat menjijikan.  Tapi tuhan benar adanya dan tidak buta, 11 maret 2011 Gempa berskala 9,0 magnitudo yang menyebabkan tsunami semoga  memberi ganjaran terhadap kalian.  Sekarang keberadaan kalian terancam punah karena menurunya indeks kelahiran dan meningkatnya para pensiunan, jujur kepunahan dan kehancuran kalian akan lumayan menarik untuk di saksikan, seperti series anime.  Pada 6 dan 9 Agustus 1945, Hiroshima dan Nagasaki mendapat ganjaran dari langit, tragedi ini sangat memuaskan bagi saya sebagai individu yang menaruh dendam terhadap kalian.  Pengeboman yang terjadi di Hiroshima dan Nagasaki melepaskan Hasrat dan harapan saya, yang ingin melihat kalian menerima konsekuensi sadis dan brutal terhadap kalian, bagaikan Do'a di kabulkan tuhan, kalian menerima karma yang memuaskan bagi saya secara pribadi. What seems crazy to me is Seattle will absolutely get an earthquake of this size at some point, and for the same geologic reasons (which is also why Mt Rainier looks like Mt Fuji, but I digress).  Difference being, Japan has an extremely long written history documenting their earthquakes and were thus extremely well prepared.  Whereas in Seattle, the culture that built the city sprang up in the short time since the last 9.0 and therefore had no idea this could happen until like last Tuesday.  They're not prepared AT ALL for the whole metro area to slide 2 meters towards Hawaii.  Fortunately tsunamis are unlikely to make it all the way into Puget Sound.  Ironically, the best record known of the last Cascadia full-rip quake comes from... Japan!  In 1700 they were quite surprised to see a tsunami come in with no earthquake.  Only recently did some Americans come poking around talking about how the mud in Washington indicated a big earthquake around 1690-1710, and did the Japanese by chance notice any big waves in those years?  Yes.  Yes indeed.

I was there from the US on a university exchange program. A bunch of us drove up to help with clean up and 3 things stick out I could never forget. The first was an older Japanese woman coming up to me with a silver bag she found on the beach covered in mostly English writing; it was a blood pack presumably from a hospital or ship, I went cold and thought of all the people in hospitals who would have had nowhere to go. I didn't know what to say so just said 'medical.' The second was just the sheer amount of tatami floor everywhere, water logged floors from countless houses. Lastly shipping containers were all over the beach sticking straight up into the air, like crooked monoliths. It felt wrong to even talk during the cleanup. As a foreigner I felt I was undeserving to be on such sacred ground. It changed me as a person and how I viewed humanity and the world.

I've experienced a very light earthquake in Kansas, of all places.  I was in Topeka, just east of Burnett's Mound.  As I approached my desk, the desk actually started moving back and forth and creaking. The computer monitor was shaking. I could see the shadow the chandelier in my living room swinging back and forth, and my Sheltie was barking quite excitedly.  At the same time, I could hear a deep roar.  I think it registered about a one on the Richter Scale.  I then checked the faults that run through Kansas, a state not associated with quakes, but there is a town west of Ft. Riley that experiences several small quakes a year.  That town happens to be right on the fault line that goes south through the foothills of the Kansas Flint Hills into Oklahoma and is the same fault that has rocked Oklahoma City a few times. What you should learn (since water doesn't always recede) is that after major earthquakes (anything that topples furniture makes cracks walls and paintings fall down or go askew) you evacuate to high ground first then wait for the news or alarm. You help only those right around you.  (Kids,old, and handicapped). You evacuate as soon as you can stand or the earthquake is stopping.  This gives you enough time (15-20 minutes to get 2-3 km inland running or to the nearest hilltops or highrises). Also as far as possible you go on foot. Cars create gridlock.

¬†@StevieC65¬† yes. But but but, it really is: "as soon as shaking is beginning to drop I leave". From the shaking ends to impact close to the epicentre it is between 10-30 minutes. You don't waste time, you don't wait for tsunami alarms, you don't pick anyone up. You evacuate helping those unable or complicated in your immediate vicinity (a neighbours child, an elderly neighbour). Others will do the same for your kids and elderly. And you go as far in and/or up as you can following the tsunami signs or if none exist according to you knowledge seeking always higher ground. It is called preventive self evacuation and should be immediately applied in any earthquake situation near coasts. If the earthquake was VI or above on the Mercalli intensity scale you don't wait for anything.

Hi, I‚Äôm Japanese and I was 4 years old when this happened.  I guess I‚Äôm fluent in English because I lived in America before. I decided to write this because recent reports say that there‚Äôs going to be a very big earthquake coming up in Japan in the next 10 to 30 years. By the way I‚Äôm copying and pasting this to most of the Great East Japan Earthquake videos I can find, so that many people can read it :)  4 years old is the age when I was in preschool (or kindergarten?), and I was on my mom‚Äôs bicycle (in japan, there are these kinds of bicycles called mamachari that most moms with kids have, and they have seats where kids can sit at the back or the front). Anyways, I don‚Äôt remember what I saw or felt at that time because I was so young plus I was sleeping... but my mom recently told me that the utility poles were shaking sideways, even though we lived in a place that was about 400km (248.55 miles) away from where the earthquake occurred.  and I think you guys know, but Japan suffers from A LOT of earthquakes. Earthquakes with the magnitude of 1 to 5 are quite normal for us because they happen all the time. But that doesn‚Äôt mean that we‚Äôre not scared of them. We definitely get scared and worried because we know big, tragic earthquakes can happen. Some people have traumas, because their mom, dad, sister, brother, grandma, grandpa, friend, or pet passed away from an earthquake. or maybe because they witnessed big earthquakes or tsunamis before.  In this 3.11.2011 Great East Japan Earthquake, more than 22,000 people have been reported dead or missing.  Every Japanese citizen pray and mourn the loss of the victims on March 11th.  Humans actually lose their lives from natural disasters like this, and in this case of earthquakes, people can die from 1)drowning from tsunamis 2)hit/squashed by furniture that fell to the ground (suffocation) 3)burned to death (by fire) 4)other diseases caused when a person spends their time at the evacuation shelter too much (this especially happens to old people/ the elderly, because they often have chronic illnesses/diseases.)  I don‚Äôt know where you‚Äôre from, but some of you might think ‚Äúwow this is so scary, but big earthquakes won‚Äôt happen in my country. we‚Äôre totally fine.‚Äù. I know, I really know- that earthquakes are rare in some countries. But I feel like it‚Äôs still better to prepare for them. In Japan, buildings have become stronger than ever, and citizens have prepared things just in case. Most of us have emergency kits/bags to bring outside when disasters happen. In Tokyo Disneyland, all employees participate in evacuation drills that are held about once in two days.  What I‚Äôm trying to say is, preparation is necessary.. but even if we prepare a lot, sometimes we can‚Äôt win against nature.  Sorry for writing this long. Thank you for all of the support ‚Äî with money, materials, or words ‚Äî people all around the world have given us. STAY SAFE FROM COVID!!

I was a 15-16 years old United States resident around the time of the tsunami. In the following months, a video surfaced about a UCLA student who made a racist rant against her fellow Asian students and family tradition, with one small mention of the 2011 tsunami.   In light of the the racist attacks on the Asian American community recently in March 2021, that rant video resurfaced, as if to echo the prejudice that has always been lying hidden in the United States, but it also led me personally to find out about the 2011 tsunami now that I'm in my 20s. I looked up the documentaries and videos of the tsunami for myself,  and so, for that UCLA student to make light of such a tragedy and gloss over that feeling of overwhelming despair that Japanese international students must have felt while they were rushing to contact their families, it broke my heart, and I hoped that this student really understood the gravity of what had happened by the time she took down her rant from YouTube.

I live in North Borneo, where we're surrounded by countries that has volcanoes and have frequent earthquakes (Indonesia and the Philippines), but our island is quite sheltered so we don't really have earthquakes and even if they do happen, we never notice because the scale is just too small to even feel...  Then came June 5th 2015...an earthquake happened with a magnitude of 6.0, and the hardest hit was Mount Kinabalu...there were many climbers that day, and many died on the mountain, most of them schoolchildren from Singapore and the mountain guides that tried to save their climbers...I live about 70km from the epicenter, and we clearly felt the quake...we had never experienced earthquake before, we didn't really know what to do...you're supposed to run outside to a safe area, preferably a clearing, but me and my mom just stayed inside our house, panicking...luckily we were very far inland and our district is surrounded by two mountain ranges so there was never a tsunami threat...  The earthquake lasted about 30 seconds, and a few more aftershocks happened after the first big earthquake....our house had a few cracks on the wall due to the earthquake, but other than that, nothing else was damaged..houses at the epicenter were badly damaged, though...houses here in North Borneo were never built to withstand earthquake because there was never the need, but after that, buildings have been re-evaluated and buildings built after the earthquake that are taller than two-stories need to be earthquake-proof...  That incident served as a wake-up call for us...all these times, we thought we were safe from earthquakes and tsunamis because we're not located within The Ring of Fire, but recently, offshore earthquakes are happening more frequently, and small tremors that happen are no longer treated carelessly....every time small shocks are detected, we are warned to be ready to evacuate immediately because it might be a sign that a bigger earthquake might happen...

If you are living in active plate tectonic boundaries, always prepare for major earthquakes. Japan is located in active subduction zone (which is also the same for the Philippines, Taiwan, and Indonesia for Asian regions; Northwestern US coast as well). To look for subduction zones, any volcanic features are the biggest hint (except Hawaii or Iceland or Yellowstone National Park because those are volcanic hotspots from intraplate rising magma toward surface). From Washington State to Humboldt / Mendocino CA, subduction zone is present because you'll see active volcanism in coastal inland areas. Landslides and floods are devastating as well. I live in CA, and we may not have major source for tsunami because vertical displacement under deep coastal water in subduction zone region is the biggest cause for tsunami. But, rising sea level from global warming will affect coastal communities. In CA, from the Bay Area to SoCal, we have the San Andreas fault system, with Hayward fault and minor faults where earthquakes occur and can cause massive disaster. Preparedness is the key to survival.

A shock wave of energy, here from two tectonic plates moving against each other, can travel through the ground at way higher speeds than energy moving through the air such as sound. It's just a fact in physics: energy waves in form of vibrations travels better through solid objects than they do through gases such as air. Lots of people live where wildfires occur in California, and yet we still hear about rich people like celebrities' homes being affected. Florida, Texas, Louisiana and a bunch other southern states are hit hard by hurricanes each year. Central US has tornadoes, northern states have snowstorms, mountainous regions have avalanches, areas with soft ground are subject to mudslides, not to mention all the earthquakes that occur around plate lines..... And if not problems with the natural environment, then there's problems with the people, like in the city where there's high crime rates and crowding issues and pollution. The magnitude scale is logarithmic. That just means that if you add 1 to an earthquake's magnitude, you multiply the shaking by 10. An earthquake of magnitude 5 shakes 10 times as violently as an earthquake of magnitude 4; a magnitude-6 quake shakes 10 times as hard as a magnitude-5 quake; and so on.   To compare two earthquakes in terms of shaking, you subtract one magnitude from the other and raise 10 to that power: 10^(M1-M2).   For example, if the magnitude of one quake is 6 and another is 4, than the difference in magnitudes is 2, so the stronger earthquake shakes 10^2 or 100 times as hard as the milder one.

Dankrupt I had something alike in my city. It wasn't that catastrophic in terms of lives or structures, but I can try to explain. I had the luck of living in the highest zone, suddenly power goes off. Being a nerd I go out on the balcony, swearing, and the first thing I see is cars and scraps being carried away by brownish water. The garages are exploding under the water pressure resulting in suffering metal roars. People are screaming everywhere. Always seen such things only on tv, moments between panic and realization, and Plinius the Elder in me ventures outside to admire the ruthless power of nature. Plan was basically running back at the smallest sign of water rising,  but I had to see it. I stuck around until night, the water level stabilized, and saw how the city reacted. The saving boats trying to evacuate blocked citizens hiding on higher floors in the case the building crumbled puzzled me. Where once was landscape now was water. I would lie if I said I remember everything. The memory consists of scattered moments, with unexplainable, unmeasurable curiosity and excitement. I cannot say for sure, but the water level arose minimum 20-22 meters and lasted minimum 7/8 hours (I used one bridge as reference). This was caused by a voluntary, desperate but necessary dam opening after many days of red alarm. Most of my city was built ignoring security measures along the river, as a result of corruption and laziness. I lost nothing, but many people I know lost their house and car. The victim count should be less than 10, 'cause luckily the water didn't really manage to make bigger building crumble. The community reunited itself after the tragedy and rebuilt anew. My point of view was, obviously, a lucky one, and therefore I cannot describe you how does it feel to be fighting for life, but once I realized I was safe, I was mesmerized by such power.

Chaise LaBrie respectfully, I am not a scientist but a lay person. My understanding is that waves in the deep ocean are essentially sound waves traveling through water. The speed of 5 miles per second refers to the speed attained as the shock wave ‚Äòsound wave‚Äô travels through the deep ocean. As the energy begins to hit shallower water, the wave speed slows down but then that energy it converted to wave size. You may now see that the speed of a solid bullet traveling through air is perhaps not an accurate comparison to energy waves passing through air or water. You may have experienced that given calm wind conditions, the ‚Äòsound‚Äô of a rifle will arrive faster than the actual bullet. Again, not claiming to be an authority or trying to be a smarty pants, just giving my understanding of tsunamis. Do a google on speed of sound. Quite interesting. The Cascadia subduction zone fault along the west coast of the U.S. and Canada would be North Americas largest disaster IF a full rupture of that fault occurs. It has been locked for 319 years and science have a 3d visual of what that looks like today.Until all of the infrastructure gets built up to standard a full rupture may take some cities so a 9.0 displaces 120,000 square miles a 9.2 180-188-000 square miles like the alaskan event in Prince William Sound.Nothing in California can match the energy released not even San Andreas. For the backside of that tsunami then involves a large portion of the Pacific Ocean Hawaii, Alaska its Islands Korea Russia Japan around 16 feet there at a 9.0 Cascadia event similar to the 1700 orphan tsunami. It finishes in the Sumatra Papa New Guinea before gravity can lessen these columns of water. Usually Cascadia ruptures south to north along the 620 mile long fault Japans Tokohu fault ruptured 500 kilometers at a momentum magnitude of 9.1 NHK/USGS. It picked up a column of water approximately 6 billion cubic meters worth and ejected it outward in all directions at a great rate of speed. These columns of water can go up and over land masses or what they call refract off a landmass and combine with another column of water. Usually the main wave or high wave will be found within the first 4 columns of water but they persist for many hours and with 2 tide cycles its gradual. So my advice if you shake for 5 minutes or more program the brain to get your legs to 150 to 200 feet don't focus on the height of the waves its the high water marks that matter with that much water volume. Lets hope this doesn't slip but its 80 years past the small event and that being in the 8.0's to low as 7.9, some partial ruptures can still involve 40-70% of that 620 mile long fault. Lot of people gonna call me names after this, but im just stating the cold hard fact. 2 countries, one have 120+ mil population the other have 220+ mil, both are no strangers to tsunami and eartquake, both are sitting on top of active tectonic plate. Both were hit with powerful quake (9.0 vs 9.1) and tsunami. The difference is, 1 is prepared.  Japan quake+tsunami, roughly 28,000 dead/missing. Most of the infrastructure, except for the wooden traditional houses survives.   Indonesian quake+tsunami, roughly 160,000 dead/missing and all major infrastructure are either collapsed by the quake or swept away by the tidal wave.  One country knew its only a matter of time before another disaster is coming, the other barely prepared for it. One country have active early warning system and train its citizen for things to do during quake and tsunamis, the other have none.   One country learn from the previous disaster, implementing changes to better equipped its infrastructure and shoreline from the next coming disaster, the other cant even properly maintain its warning system.   The result is clear, nearly 6x the total deathtoll/missing simply because one government took things seriously while the other are too busy playing politics.

The tectonic plates are unstable due to minings, tunneling, transfering large amount of earth ,  destroying its equilibrium can cause earthquakes, tsunamis, typhoons, volcanic eruptions, etc.. Why? Let's consider a single plate(tectonic plate) that is in equilibrium meaning at rest.If you remove some of its weight and transfer them somewhere, you're making it unbalanced. The result is earthquake or volcanic eruptions. If some of the plate's boundaries are located under the sea, possibilities are tsunamis and typhoons . Why? When the sea bed have cracked the melting earth (lava ) will be exposed directly to the water  causing heavy water vapor to create typhoons and tsunami is caused by quaking seabed. All objects have its boundaries and center of gravity (point of balance) or we can call it  focal point, so when a plate's gradual unbalancement( continue), byfar, earthquake will occur. If the boundary lines are nearer to the focal point the earthquake intensity is lower as compared to the farder boundary lines, the fardest boundary lines will suffer much more earthquake intensity .  Somewhere ,near  or above the focal point earthquake movement  is horizontal,  while in every boundaries vertical movement will be sensed. After shocks earthquaking is cause by the changing point of gravity and we sense the grinding of every boundaries first before the shaking of the earth.

I had it about 15 minutes after this earthquake went off‚ÄîI was California‚Äîand the sickness actually woke me up, and got me checking the news. I know labs can simulate these things, but the LAST thing I will ever do is volunteer for some study to see what vestigial cells I carry. The sensation doesn‚Äôt make me want to run uphill. The seawall mentioned is not 18 feet above sea sevel, it's only about 12 feet, and the depth of the waves exceeding the sea wall was only another couple of meters, as even this video shows.  The Japanese tsunami was a major disaster because of the extensive development and population at sea level along the coast.
